05119nam a22009015i 9780520922310DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209223107 a10.1525/97805209223102doi  a(DE-B1597)519777  a(OCoLC)1109319959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBF1472.G8bJ64 1999eb 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a133.1/09382211 aJohnston, Sarah Iles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRestless Dead :bEncounters between the Living and the Dead in Ancient Greece /cSarah Iles Johnston. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tAcknowledgments -- tFrequently Used Terms -- tAbbreviations -- tPART I. A SHORT HISTORY OF THE DEAD IN ANCIENT GREECE -- t1. Elpenor and Others: Narrative Descriptions of the Dead -- t2. To Honor and Avert: Rituals Addressed to the Dead -- t3. Magical Solutions to Deadly Problems: The Origin and Roles of the Goes -- tPART II. RESTLESS DEAD -- t4. The Unavenged: Dealing with Those Who Die Violently -- t5. Childless Mothers and Blighted Virgins: Female Ghosts and Their Victims -- tPART III. DIVINITIES AND THE DEAD -- t6. Hecate and the Dying Maiden: How the Mistress of Ghosts Earned Her Title -- t7. Purging the Polis: Erinyes, Eumenides, and Semnai Theai -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum -- tTexts -- tInscriptions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the archaic and classical periods, Greek ideas about the dead evolved in response to changing social and cultural conditions—most notably changes associated with the development of the polis, such as funerary legislation, and changes due to increased contacts with cultures of the ancient Near East. In Restless Dead, Sarah Iles Johnston presents and interprets these changes, using them to build a complex picture of the way in which the society of the dead reflected that of the living, expressing and defusing its tensions, reiterating its values and eventually becoming a source of significant power for those who knew how to control it. She draws on both well-known sources, such as Athenian tragedies, and newer texts, such as the Derveni Papyrus and a recently published lex sacra from Selinous.Topics of focus include the origin of the goes (the ritual practitioner who made interaction with the dead his specialty), the threat to the living presented by the ghosts of those who died dishonorably or prematurely, the development of Hecate into a mistress of ghosts and its connection to female rites of transition, and the complex nature of the Erinyes. Restless Dead culminates with a new reading of Aeschylus' Oresteia that emphasizes how Athenian myth and cult manipulated ideas about the dead to serve political and social ends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGhostszGreecexHistory. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aafterlife.  aancient greece.  aancient history.  aancient texts.  aancient world.  aarchaic.  aathens.  aclassical period.  acultural studies.  adeath.  aderveni papyrus.  afunerary.  afunereal.  agovernment.  agreek drama.  agreek history.  agreek tragedy.  alife and death.  amyth.  amythology.  anear east.  apolis.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apower.  arituals.  ascholarly.  asocial studies.  asociety.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021707240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092231040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922310423C